Aly Energy Services, Inc. Key Developments

Aly Energy Services, Inc. Announces Management Changes
Feb 16 17
Effective December 12, 2016, Aly Energy Services, Inc. announced that Nadine Smith resigned as a member of board of directors. On January 30, 2017 and in contemplation of the closing of the Recap, board of directors implemented the following changes of Shauvik Kundagrami was elected Chief Executive Officer and a member of the board of directors; provided that, the effective date of his election as Chief Executive Officer will be determined at a later date, but prior to May 1, 2017; Micki Hidayatallah will serve as Chief Executive Officer until the effective date of Mr. Kundagrami’s election to the position. Mr. Hidayatallah will remain Executive Chairman of the Board; Ali Afdhal resigned as a member of the board of directors but will continue to assist the Company as an emeritus director; Bryan Dutt was added to the board of directors; and Greg Price was elected as Chief Operating Officer. Shauvik Kundagrami, 53 years of age, has served as co-head of the energy group at RBC for the prior 10 years. Bryan Dutt, 57 years of age, is the Founder and President of Ironman Energy Capital Management, LLC, which he founded in 1999. Greg Price, 65 years of age, has served as a Special Advisor to the CEO of the company since April 2016.


Aly Energy Services, Inc. Elects Christopher Quinn to Serve as Chief Restructuring Officer
Aug 10 16
Effective August 5, 2016, the board of Aly Energy Services, Inc. elected Christopher Quinn to serve as chief restructuring officer of the company. Mr. Quinn was retained in this capacity pursuant to an engagement letter the company entered into with The Claro Group LLC to assist it and its lender in evaluating financial and restructuring alternatives, as mandated by the forbearance agreement.


Aly Energy Services Seeking to Sell Asset or Equity Capital
May 25 16
Aly Energy Services, Inc. (OTCPK: ALYE) is seeking to sell its assets or equity capital yielding net cash proceeds of at least $2.5 million.The company said, "We previously reported that we entered into a forbearance agreement with Wells Fargo Bank which required us to hire an independent financial advisor and, together with such advisor, to present Wells Fargo Bank, on or before May 25, 2016, a detailed plan for asset sales or equity capital yielding net cash proceeds of at least $2.5 million. On May 25, 2016, we and our financial advisor submitted such plan to Wells Fargo Bank. The plan outlines (i) the steps taken to restructure operations, sales and administrative functions, (ii) the timetable and alternative channels being considered for the private sale of equipment and (iii) the timetable and general terms of a potential private offering of equity or equity-based securities. The plan must be acceptable to our lenders in order for the forbearance period to remain in effect until July 10, 2016, or such later date as may be determined by the lenders in any future extension of the forbearance period."


